Anne,<br><br>
I feel a little awkward writing this.  I usually do real well keeping out of other people's personal business.<br><br>
Ed's right about the red flags.  There a quite a few from what you wrote on this thread.<br><br>
You might want to give some thought about why you are in thiis relationship.  It took me a long time not to be a rescuer in a relationship.  My good friends kid me about it.  I confess to be a frustrated idealist -- always trying to make &quot;things&quot; better.  My personality comes from my youth.  I could have been born that way.  I'm not sure.  Could have come from trying to make life &quot;fair.&quot;  How many times did you hear the words from your three kids, &quot;hey mom, that's not fair.&quot;<br><br>
Love works best when partners have equal (as it can be) footing.  There's lots of good books out there and tons of advice, more than enough for a hundred lifetimes.  You take something away from someone when you rescue them.<br><br>
We all love you here.  I think you know that.  We all vie for the honor of being &quot;Mom's favorite,&quot; and that's fine and fun.  But we really don't need a mother or want one.  Your value to us (me) is being our friend.<br><br>
Paul
